Epiproct (Fig. 
5
). Paraprocts generally flat, ornamented with about six vertical small ridges each bearing a single row of tiny tubercles; basal third of surface abruptly angled outward to lie in a plane with the hypoproct; latter subtriangular, with two prominent digitiform paramedian processes. Legs attached to strongly elevated, densely setose podosterna, condyles not produced as subcoxal spines. Sides of metazona nearly smooth, at most with sparse indistinct tubercles. Legs uniformly invested with sparse, long, erect setae.

Gonopod aperture (
Fig. 11
) transversely oval, not intruding onto stricture, lateral ends and posterior edge elevated. Gonopods stout, contiguous in situ (
Fig. 11
), extended forward to sternum of segment 6 , coxa black on anterior surface, white on ventral, with a single long, simple seta on the dorsal surface; telopodite nearly black except for clear testaceous apical lamina. Shape of apical lamina (
Fig. 12
) similar to that of
P. fasciolatus
(Fig. 13 ), but slightly smaller as seen in mesal aspect..
